🧠 What is a String?

A string is a sequence of characters — like text, words, or sentences.

Example:

let name = "Krishna";

Here, "Krishna" is a string.

💡 Common String Methods in JavaScript

1️⃣ length

👉 Finds how many characters are in a string.

let name = "Krishna";
console.log(name.length);  // Output: 7

2️⃣ toUpperCase()

👉 Converts all letters to capital letters.

let name = "krishna";
console.log(name.toUpperCase()); // Output: KRISHNA

3️⃣ toLowerCase()

👉 Converts all letters to small letters.

let city = "PUNE";
console.log(city.toLowerCase()); // Output: pune

4️⃣ trim()

👉 Removes extra spaces from both sides of a string.

let name = "   Krishna   ";
console.log(name.trim()); // Output: "Krishna"

5️⃣ slice(start, end)

👉 Cuts a part (portion) of a string.

let name = "Krishna";
console.log(name.slice(0, 3)); // Output: "Kri"

6️⃣ replace(oldText, newText)

👉 Changes part of the string with something else.

let message = "Hello World";
console.log(message.replace("World", "Krishna")); // Output: Hello Krishna

7️⃣ concat()

👉 Joins two or more strings together.

let first = "Hello";
let second = "World";
console.log(first.concat(" ", second)); // Output: Hello World

8️⃣ charAt(index)

👉 Finds the character at a specific position.

let name = "Krishna";
console.log(name.charAt(0)); // Output: K

9️⃣ indexOf("text")

👉 Tells the position (index) of a specific word or letter.

let city = "Pune City";
console.log(city.indexOf("City")); // Output: 5

🔟 includes("text")

👉 Checks if a word or letter is present or not.

let sentence = "I love JavaScript";
console.log(sentence.includes("love")); // true

🌟 Bonus: split()

👉 Splits a string into parts and makes an array.

let fruits = "apple,banana,grape";
console.log(fruits.split(",")); // Output: ["apple", "banana", "grape"]

11 > toString()

👉 Converts object to string format.

(123).toString(); // "123"

12 > includes(text)

👉 Checks if a text exists (true/false).

"Hello".includes("He") // true

13 > repeat(n)

👉 Repeats string n times.

"Hi ".repeat(3) // "Hi Hi Hi "

14 > startsWith(text)

👉 Checks if string starts with given text.

"Hello".startsWith("He") // true

15 > endsWith(text)

👉 Checks if string ends with given text.

"Hello".endsWith("lo") // true

16 > replaceAll(oldText, newText)

👉 Replaces all matches of a word.

"apple apple".replaceAll("apple", "banana") // "banana banana"
